The '''Embassy of Canada to Croatia''' in [[Zagreb]] is the [[List of diplomatic missions of Canada|diplomatic mission of Canada]] to [[Croatia]]. This embassy also represents Canadian diplomatic relations with [[Kosovo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada-Kosovo Relations|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/croatia-croatie/bilateral_relations_bilaterales/Canada_Kosovo_relations.aspx?menu_id=37&view=d|accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref> Visas for immigration to Canada are not processed in Zagreb, as they are processed at the Visa Section of the Embassy of Canada to Austria in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Visa and Immigration|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/croatia-croatie/visas/index.aspx?lang=eng&menu_id=3&view=d|accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref>

==Building==

The building in which the embassy is located is rented from the [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Serbian orthodox]] [[Metropolitanate of Zagreb and Ljubljana]].<ref name="Mitropolija">{{cite web|url=http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=34&lang=sr |language= Serbian| title=Nekretnine Mitropolije Zagrebačko-ljubljanske u Zagrebu |publisher=[[Metropolitanate of Zagreb and Ljubljana]]|date= |accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref> The building was built between 1886 and 1887, and it was architecturally designed by Kuno Vajdman.<ref name="Mitropolija"></ref> 

By the beginning of the [[War in Croatia]], the building was the seat of the metropolitanate and its museum, archive and library.<ref name="Mitropolija"></ref> On April 11, 1992, the building was dynamited, after which the seat of the metropolitanate was moved to another building.<ref name="Mitropolija"></ref> After the metropolitanate restored the building, they rented it to the embassy.<ref name="Mitropolija"></ref>

