{{Infobox prepared food | name = ''Hortobágyi palacsinta | image = Hortobagy palacsinta.JPG | image_size = 250px | caption = | alternate_name = | country = [[Hungary]] | region = [[Hungary]] [[Alföld]]| creator = | course = | type = [[Pancake]] | served = | main_ingredient = Meat (usually [[veal]]), [[onion]]s, [[spice]]s, [[Black pepper|pepper]] and [[sour cream]] | variations = | calories = | other = }}
'''''Hortobágyi palacsinta''''' is a [[Umami|savoury]] [[Hungarian cuisine|Hungarian]] [[Palatschinken|pancake]], filled with meat (usually [[veal]]). The meat is prepared as a stew; minced meat is fried with onions and spices like the ''[[Goulash|pörkölt]]'' or the ''paprikás'' dish, using veal, veal with mushrooms, chicken, or [[Kolbász|Hungarian sausage]].The pancakes are filled with the minced meat, tucking in the ends, and are baked in the oven with a [[paprika]]<ref name="Bennitt 2010 p. 584">{{cite book | last=Bennitt | first=L. | title=The Rough Guide to Europe On A Budget | publisher=Rough Guides Limited | series=Music rough guide | year=2010 | isbn=978-1-84836-458-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u9jxc274bRQC&pg=PA584 | page=584}}</ref> and [[Smetana (dairy product)|''tejföl'']] (sour cream) sauce, then topped with fresh parsley.<ref>{{cite web|title=HORTOBÁGYI PALACSINTA|url=http://www.manusmenu.com/hortobagyi-palacsinta|website=manusmenu.com|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>
The dish does not originate from the [[Hortobágy National Park]] region of the [[Great Hungarian Plain]] and has nothing to do with Hortobágy. It was originally invented for the [[Expo 58|1958 Brussels World Fair]]. However, some Hungarian recipe books already featured a similar recipe in the 1930s. The name of the food is simply a marketing trick.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}
